LAYER 3: TONGUE
taste and speech

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the tongue is a muscular organ in the oral cavity serving two critical functions:
gustation taste the chemical sensing of food and liquid
articulation the shaping of sound into speech
the tongue is innervated by five cranial nerves making it one of the most neurally complex organs in the body
motor innervation: CN XII hypoglossal for all intrinsic and most extrinsic muscles except palatoglossus CN X
taste from the anterior two-thirds: CN VII facial via chorda tympani
taste from the posterior one-third: CN IX glossopharyngeal
taste from the epiglottic region: CN X vagus
general sensation from the anterior two-thirds: CN V₃ mandibular branch of trigeminal

STRUCTURE intrinsic_muscles | four pairs | change the SHAPE of the tongue | superior longitudinal inferior longitudinal transverse and vertical | all innervated by CN XII
STRUCTURE extrinsic_muscles | four pairs | change the POSITION of the tongue
    genioglossus | protrudes and depresses the tongue | CN XII
    hyoglossus | depresses and retracts the tongue | CN XII
    styloglossus | retracts and elevates the posterior tongue | CN XII
    palatoglossus | elevates the posterior tongue and depresses the palate | CN X via pharyngeal plexus

TASTE BUDS approximately 5000-10000 taste buds in the oral cavity
each taste bud contains 50-100 taste receptor cells surrounded by supporting cells and basal stem cells
taste receptor cells are replaced every 10-14 days from basal stem cells
taste buds are concentrated on the tongue within papillae but also found on the palate pharynx and epiglottis

PAPILLAE
fungiform | scattered on anterior two-thirds | each contains 3-5 taste buds | innervated by chorda tympani CN VII
circumvallate | 7-12 large papillae arranged in a V-shape at the posterior tongue | each contains hundreds of taste buds | innervated by CN IX
foliate | lateral edges of the posterior tongue | contain taste buds | innervated by CN IX
filiform | most numerous | cover the entire dorsum | NOT taste buds | mechanical for texture detection and food manipulation

FIVE BASIC TASTES each mediated by specific receptor mechanisms on taste receptor cells

TASTE sweet | T1R2 + T1R3 heterodimer GPCR | Gₐ gustducin → phospholipase Cβ₂ → IP₃ → Ca²⁺ release from ER → TRPM5 cation channel opens → depolarization → ATP released through CALHM1 channels as neurotransmitter | signals caloric density | sugar
TASTE umami | T1R1 + T1R3 heterodimer GPCR | same transduction cascade as sweet | signals protein content | glutamate | the taste of meat broth and aged cheese
TASTE bitter | T2R family approximately 25 different GPCRs | same gustducin pathway as sweet | signals potential toxins | the broadest receptor family because there are many different toxic molecules | low threshold high sensitivity
TASTE sour | OTOP1 proton channel | H⁺ ions flow directly through the channel | depolarization | signals acid | spoiled food | also Zn²⁺-sensitive proton channels on type III cells
TASTE salt | epithelial sodium channel ENaC | Na⁺ flows directly through the channel | depolarization | signals mineral content | essential electrolytes

TASTE PATHWAY
taste receptor cells synapse with primary gustatory afferent fibers
CN VII → geniculate ganglion → tractus solitarius → nucleus of the solitary tract NTS in the medulla
CN IX → petrosal ganglion → NTS
CN X → nodose ganglion → NTS
NTS → ventral posteromedial nucleus of thalamus VPM → primary gustatory cortex in the anterior insula and frontal operculum
NTS also projects to the hypothalamus for feeding behavior and to the amygdala for hedonic evaluation

the anterior insula processes taste quality "what does this taste like"
the orbitofrontal cortex processes palatability "do I like this"
the amygdala tags taste with emotional valence
the hypothalamus integrates taste with hunger and satiety signals

at 24 months:
taste sensitivity is high particularly for sweet and bitter
sweet preference is innate from birth promoting caloric intake
bitter aversion is innate from birth preventing toxin ingestion
food preferences are being established through repeated exposure
the child may require 10-15 exposures to a new food before accepting it
this is neophobia and it is a protective adaptation not stubbornness
articulation is developing but many consonant sounds require precise tongue placement that depends on corticobulbar maturation and cerebellar timing

SENSATION sweet | "something good is on my tongue. energy. sugar."
SENSATION bitter | "warning. this might be bad. I want to spit it out."
SENSATION sour | "sharp and bright. my mouth puckers."
SENSATION salty | "minerals. my body recognizes what it needs."
SENSATION umami | "rich and deep. this tastes like food. real food."
SENSATION disgusting | "everything in me says no. the taste is wrong."
SENSATION delicious | "I want more. this taste is satisfying something deep."

pulse gustatory_heartbeat:
    when food touches the tongue:
        tastant molecules dissolve in saliva
        they reach taste receptor cells in taste buds within papillae
        each taste modality activates its specific receptor mechanism:
            sweet and umami and bitter via GPCR → gustducin → PLCβ₂ → IP₃ → Ca²⁺ → TRPM5 → ATP
            sour via OTOP1 proton channel
            salt via ENaC sodium channel
        gustatory afferent fibers in CN VII IX and X carry the signal to the NTS
        NTS relays to VPM thalamus
        VPM relays to gustatory cortex in the anterior insula
        the brain knows what it tastes
        the amygdala decides how it feels about it
        the hypothalamus decides whether to eat more

    when articulating speech:
        motor cortex sends commands via corticobulbar tract to CN XII nucleus
        the hypoglossal nerve activates intrinsic and extrinsic muscles
        the tongue changes shape and position hundreds of times per sentence
        alveolar sounds /t/ /d/ /n/ /l/ require tongue tip on the alveolar ridge
        velar sounds /k/ /g/ /ŋ/ require tongue back on the soft palate
        palatal sounds /j/ require tongue body on the hard palate
        the tongue is the most important articulator in speech
        at 24 months many of these placements are still being learned
